></tr></tbody></table></figure></div><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Ramp&#8217;s strategy is to a=
lign itself with customers, decrease spend, and build healthier businesses =
that can reinvest in growth. It&#8217;s the long-game, but it&#8217;s alrea=
dy working. Ramp is in the driver&#8217;s seat to own spend management for =
mid-market companies, and from there, to move upmarket. After wedging into =
companies with the corporate card, Ramp gives them new software products to=
 help control and manage spend at an astonishing rate.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Yo=
u need both -- the card and the software -- to win.</p><p style=3D"color: #=
1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Companies t=
hat stay software-only, like Expensify, are getting picked off by companies=
 like Ramp that turn its whole business into a free feature, while companie=
s that focused too heavily on corporate card sales and marketing at the exp=
ense of product, like Brex, were caught flat-footed as the card itself beca=
me table stakes.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Software companies are just faster, and that&#=
8217;s a major advantage in a massive market with essentially uncapped upsi=
de. In a market like that, winning is all about trajectory and velocity. Ne=
w features help acquire new customers, and retain and delight existing ones=
 by saving them money.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">How does Ramp ship so fast? People.&nbsp=
;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 1em 0;">When Karim, Eric, and I had our first conversation about this=
 piece, Karim highlighted how they think about hiring: &#8220;We hire peopl=
e for potential and growth trajectory, slope over intercept. We make bets o=
n people. The goal is not zero defects, but 10x potential.&#8221;&nbsp;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 1em 0;">The team today, at 85 employees, is absurdly talented. One-third o=
f the team are former founders, and at least five people on the team gradua=
ted with perfect GPAs from MIT, Stanford, Harvard, and other top schools. T=
he team also includes a few dropouts. Overall, the team skews heavily towar=
ds engineering and design. That, plus conversation with angels and customer=
s, has allowed them to ship at an unbelievable cadence.&nbsp;</p><p style=
